field_temperature_measures

Fabian C. Salgado-Roa

2024-02-08

Termal differences black morph vs black-and-white morph in the field

load tidyverse and input with all measures

library(tidyverse)
measures<-read_csv("C:/Users/Fabian C. Salgado/Dropbox/PhD_FabianSalgado/research_proposal/aim2/thermal_photos/2023_ballarat/field_form.csv")

Define a function to calculate standard error

se <- function(x) {
  sd(x) / sqrt(length(x))
}

This file has dorsal and ventral measures for multiple variables of both black and black-and-white morph. The variables we measured in the field were:

wind_v=Ventral wind speed
wind_d=Ventral wind speed
temp_v=Temperature ventral side
temp_d=Temperature ventral side
light_v=Light recieved ventral side
light_d=Light recieved dorsal side
height=Height at which the individual was at time of measure
wind_temp_v=Temperature of wind at time of measure on ventral side
wind_temp_d=Temperature of wind at time of measure on dorsal side

We will explore the differences in temperature between morphs per side

Field Termal differences

We will explore the differences in temperature between morphs per side

Ventral side

Before running the model lets explore the correlation between the predictors

Explore a correlation plot

cor_matrix <- cor(na.omit(measures[,c("wind_v","light_v","height","wind_temp_v")]))

colnames(cor_matrix)<-c("wind_v","light_v","height","wind_temp_v")

rownames(cor_matrix)<-c("wind_v","light_v","height","wind_temp_v")

corrplot::corrplot(cor_matrix, method = "number", type = "upper", order = "original", tl.cex=1, )

The predictors do not seem to have high correlations

ventral_temp <- lm(temp_v ~ wind_v+light_v+height+wind_temp_v+morph, data=measures)

performance::check_collinearity(ventral_temp)

There is low correlation!!!

Now lets build the model

ventral_temp <- lm(temp_v ~ wind_v+light_v+height+wind_temp_v+morph, data=measures)
summary(ventral_temp)

## Call:
## lm(formula = temp_v ~ wind_v + light_v + height + wind_temp_v + 
##     morph, data = measures)

anova(ventral_temp)
par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(ventral_temp)

No differences between morphs. The body temperature is correlated with the wind temperature and wind speed

measures$temp_v_predict <- predict(ventral_temp, type = "response")

Lets explore with a graph the significant association

w_col<-"gray"
b_col<-"black"
par(mfrow=c(1,1))
ggplot(data = measures, aes(x = wind_temp_v, y = temp_v, col = morph))+geom_point(size=2)+geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE)+scale_colour_manual(values = c("black" = b_col,"white" = w_col))+theme_classic()+labs(x="Wind temperature (C)",y="Ventral body temperature (C)")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Now differences between morphs

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
w_col<-"gray"
b_col<-"black"
ggplot(data = measures, aes(x = morph, y = temp_v, fill = morph)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d(option = "D") +
  geom_violin(alpha = 0.4, position = position_dodge(width = .75), size = 1) +
  geom_point(shape = 21, size = 4, position = position_jitterdodge(jitter.width = 0.15, jitter.height = 0.01), alpha = 0.5) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("black" = b_col,"white" = w_col))+
  stat_summary(
    fun = mean,
    aes(x = morph, y = temp_v_predict , color = morph, group = morph),
    fun.min = function(x) mean(x) - 2 * se(x),
    fun.max = function(x) mean(x) + 2 * se(x),
    geom = "pointrange",
    position = position_dodge(width = .75),
    size = 1.5
  ) +
  theme_classic()+
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("black" = b_col,"white" = w_col))+labs(x="Colour morph",y="Ventral body temperature (C)")
